00:04:52.220 --> 00:04:56.980
Well, Ben, something I thought might be interesting to kind of kick off the conversation with

00:04:56.980 --> 00:05:03.779
as we're getting questions from everybody here is I know that you were a consultant

00:05:03.779 --> 00:05:04.779
in a previous role.

00:05:04.779 --> 00:05:10.100
It might be good to hear a little bit about your journey, but I'd also love to hear, like,

00:05:10.100 --> 00:05:15.739
what was it like transitioning from data science as a consultant to data science in

00:05:15.739 --> 00:05:17.940
the pharma industry too?

00:05:17.940 --> 00:05:25.019
Yeah, so how I became a data scientist is pretty funny.

00:05:25.019 --> 00:05:32.179
I went to a university, I studied, like, quantitative economics and geospatial information systems

00:05:32.179 --> 00:05:37.940
and became a GIS developer right out of college working for the United States Postal Service

00:05:37.940 --> 00:05:39.420
on a federal contract.

00:05:39.739 --> 00:05:42.899
And I worked on, like, route optimization.

00:05:42.899 --> 00:05:44.779
And I was like, this is pretty cool.

00:05:44.779 --> 00:05:46.299
I really like doing this.

00:05:46.299 --> 00:05:51.260
And then the term, like, big data came around and people became data scientists.

00:05:51.260 --> 00:05:54.660
And I thought to myself, oh, wow, that's pretty cool.

00:05:54.660 --> 00:06:00.019
Maybe I should just do that instead of, like, being a GIS developer and kind of really get

00:06:00.019 --> 00:06:01.739
into data.

00:06:01.739 --> 00:06:08.540
So that's what I end up doing is deciding, all right, I'm going to focus more on data.

00:06:08.540 --> 00:06:12.140
I can always go back to GIS later, but really focus on trying to understand, like, how do

00:06:12.140 --> 00:06:16.380
I deal with really large data sets to solve different problems?

00:06:16.380 --> 00:06:19.299
So I ended up becoming a consultant.

00:06:19.299 --> 00:06:24.980
I worked in commercial consulting specifically for cybersecurity clients, building out, like,

00:06:24.980 --> 00:06:30.980
different tools, platforms, implementing machine learning methodologies, things like that.

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:37.540
And it was a really great way to get exposure to lots of different problems as well as being

00:06:37.540 --> 00:06:44.660
able to build up my skills for things, like, I might not have learned at school.

00:06:44.660 --> 00:06:52.459
And eventually what I ended up doing is transitioning into the pharma industry through a great leadership

00:06:52.459 --> 00:06:58.859
program that GSK has called the ESPRI program, which basically looks to bring outside talent

00:06:58.859 --> 00:07:04.380
who has a specific knowledge base and bring it into GSK that they want to expand upon.

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:10.579
So my cohort of ESPRI candidates, we're all data scientists, and GSK Biostats wanted to

00:07:10.579 --> 00:07:16.100
bring data science expertise in-house, and they do it through this kind of three-year

00:07:16.100 --> 00:07:17.260
leadership program.

00:07:17.260 --> 00:07:22.899
So what we do basically is we do rotational programs through different groups within the

00:07:22.899 --> 00:07:29.140
Biostats organization, bring our data science expertise, and then they teach us the pharmaceutical

00:07:29.140 --> 00:07:32.619
industry business essentially during those three years.

00:07:32.619 --> 00:07:38.779
And then at the end of the three years, you find a final position within Biostats.

00:07:38.779 --> 00:07:43.540
But it's a great way to think about, oh, this person has some, like, interesting talent

00:07:43.540 --> 00:07:46.220
that we want, but they don't have, like, the business knowledge.

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:51.739
How do we kind of marry the lack of business knowledge with the talent that we want to

00:07:51.739 --> 00:07:52.739
build?

00:07:52.739 --> 00:07:58.540
And I think that's one thing that I really love about GSK, and sorry to be like a GSK

00:07:58.540 --> 00:08:01.739
promoter right now, but being able to have that kind of space to be able to learn and

00:08:01.859 --> 00:08:06.579
develop is really crucial to being able to create, you know, those good outcomes for

00:08:06.579 --> 00:08:07.579
the business.

00:08:07.579 --> 00:08:08.579
Yeah.

00:08:08.579 --> 00:08:09.579
I'll echo what Ben said.

00:08:09.579 --> 00:08:16.579
It sounds like a great program that a lot of other companies may benefit from, too.

00:08:16.579 --> 00:08:23.179
And also realizing there's a ton of love for geospatial in the chat here, too.

00:08:23.179 --> 00:08:24.179
Yeah.

00:08:24.179 --> 00:08:31.299
That's cool to see about all the people that love GIS.

00:08:31.859 --> 00:08:36.460
I'd love to hear a little bit more about, like, what it's like going through those rotations,

00:08:36.460 --> 00:08:39.460
too, and teaching people data science.

00:08:39.460 --> 00:08:43.299
I imagine you're doing a lot of training.

00:08:43.299 --> 00:08:46.820
And what it's like, like, them teaching you the pharma side of things as well.

00:08:46.820 --> 00:08:49.419
Could you give us an example?

00:08:49.419 --> 00:08:50.700
Yeah.

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:57.619
So one of the things that came up a lot of different times was really, so if you think

00:08:57.659 --> 00:09:01.580
about pharma, we're a highly regulated industry.

00:09:01.580 --> 00:09:05.619
And I think one of the things that one of the conversations I often had with people

00:09:05.619 --> 00:09:10.859
was, well, we can't do this because we're a highly regulated industry.

00:09:10.859 --> 00:09:15.299
And to go back to your previous question about, like, what I learned from consulting, because

00:09:15.299 --> 00:09:19.140
of the nature of my work previously, I worked in highly regulated industries, but we were

00:09:19.140 --> 00:09:21.659
able to use open source tools.

00:09:21.659 --> 00:09:26.979
So I think one of the things that was really interesting going through the rotational program

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:31.340
and talking to different business groups and things like that was being able to have sort

00:09:31.340 --> 00:09:37.020
of that outside pharma industry perspective to say, like, look, you're highly regulated,

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:44.299
but so is, you know, a lot of automobile companies or oil and gas or, you know, X, Y, Z, other

00:09:44.299 --> 00:09:45.659
companies as well.

00:09:45.659 --> 00:09:48.140
And they're able to use open source tools.

00:09:48.140 --> 00:09:52.700
I think, like, you might have to think about it differently for your specific industry.

00:09:52.859 --> 00:09:58.500
But, like, you know, if you look at, like, pure accounts of regulations, I think automotive

00:09:58.500 --> 00:10:04.260
and oil and gas and financial services all have more laws and regulations compared to

00:10:04.260 --> 00:10:05.260
pharma.

00:10:05.260 --> 00:10:11.659
So I think one of the things that was interesting was going through those rotations and consistently

00:10:11.659 --> 00:10:18.820
having that conversation that, like, you don't just default because you're highly regulated.

00:10:18.820 --> 00:10:20.580
You can't use these tools.

00:10:20.580 --> 00:10:26.260
Just figuring out how do you use them safely within the organization to make sure you're

00:10:26.260 --> 00:10:28.700
satisfying those requirements.

00:10:28.700 --> 00:10:33.140
I got excited by you describing that program, and I jumped way ahead to what you learned

00:10:33.140 --> 00:10:34.140
as a consultant.

00:10:34.140 --> 00:10:40.500
But are there other things you wanted to expand on about that?

00:10:40.500 --> 00:10:43.419
What else I learned as a consultant?

00:10:43.419 --> 00:10:45.500
How to tell a good story.

00:10:45.500 --> 00:10:49.539
I think that's one thing that constantly when I'm working with data scientists who might

00:10:49.539 --> 00:10:57.059
be newer is, like, how do you tell your story about what you learned during your analysis

00:10:57.059 --> 00:11:00.380
or the outcomes or the outputs from something?

00:11:00.380 --> 00:11:05.059
I'm sure it's a trope by now, but, like, communication and being able to tell a really nice story

00:11:05.059 --> 00:11:10.900
about what it is that you did, what is it that, you know, would improve a decision maker's,

00:11:10.900 --> 00:11:13.419
you know, life is crucial.

00:11:13.419 --> 00:11:18.979
And I think one of the things that data scientists or any sort of analytics professional has

00:11:18.979 --> 00:11:23.340
to balance is, like, not only can you do the technical work, but can you do the communication

00:11:23.340 --> 00:11:27.500
and can you tell that nice story arc?

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:32.979
What's one of those communication or storytelling tips you'd share with us?

00:11:32.979 --> 00:11:34.419
Less is more.

00:11:34.419 --> 00:11:42.179
I think, like, one of the I think if you can have, like, to go back to PositConf, for everyone's

00:11:42.179 --> 00:11:48.460
awareness, like, if you do a talk at PositConf, you'll go through, like, speaker training.

00:11:48.460 --> 00:11:54.500
And one of the first trainings or maybe the second one or maybe it is just the first two,

00:11:54.500 --> 00:11:57.059
you focus on figuring out, like, what is your governing idea?

00:11:57.059 --> 00:12:02.419
Like, what is the one idea that you want everyone to walk out from after seeing your talk?

00:12:02.419 --> 00:12:09.820
And I think that should be applied to how you communicate with stakeholders.

00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:10.820
Less is more.

00:12:10.820 --> 00:12:14.979
Like, figure out, like, what it is that you want someone to walk away with based out of

00:12:14.979 --> 00:12:15.979
your meeting.

00:12:15.979 --> 00:12:21.460
Because if you're trying to show, like, a presentation, that presentation is not the

00:12:21.460 --> 00:12:24.140
only thing that that stakeholder is going to do in that day.

00:12:24.140 --> 00:12:27.539
Like, they're going to be receiving, you know, hundreds of emails per day.

00:12:27.539 --> 00:12:31.780
They are going to have to be making decisions, things like that.

00:12:31.780 --> 00:12:37.260
So the question is, like, how do you make sure that they get that one piece of crucial

00:12:37.260 --> 00:12:40.340
information you want them to have and really focus on that?

00:12:40.340 --> 00:12:42.219
So less is more.

00:12:42.219 --> 00:12:44.179
What is your one governing idea?

00:12:44.380 --> 00:12:47.700
And then everything else is just kind of, like, you know, extra gravy if you can get

00:12:47.700 --> 00:12:48.700
it.

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:54.340
But figure out what is that one thing in order to make sure that people walk away with it.

00:12:54.340 --> 00:12:55.340
Absolutely.

00:12:55.340 --> 00:13:00.460
I know a lot of people have joined since the, like, first beginning when I say how people

00:13:00.460 --> 00:13:01.460
can jump in, too.

00:13:01.460 --> 00:13:08.059
So I like to just sometimes recommend or remind people, if you have questions or things you

00:13:08.059 --> 00:13:14.460
want to add to specific topics, feel free to jump in by raising your hand here on Zoom.

00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:16.700
You can put questions in the Zoom chat.

00:13:16.700 --> 00:13:20.419
And if it's something you wanted me to read out loud instead, you can just put a little

00:13:20.419 --> 00:13:22.219
star next to it.

00:13:22.219 --> 00:13:26.500
And then Curtis or Tyler will reshare the Slido link in a second, too, if you wanted

00:13:26.500 --> 00:13:30.299
to ask anything anonymously as well.

