But Yanan, I see you asked a question here in the chat.

00:13:39.219 --> 00:13:40.219
Do you want to jump in?

00:13:40.219 --> 00:13:41.219
Hi.

00:13:41.219 --> 00:13:42.219
Hi, Rachel.

00:13:42.219 --> 00:13:43.219
Hi, Ben.

00:13:43.219 --> 00:13:44.219
Hey.

00:13:44.219 --> 00:13:45.219
Nice to see you.

00:13:45.219 --> 00:13:46.219
Yeah.

00:13:46.219 --> 00:13:52.219
I have a question regarding the R validation for the regulatory submission to FDA.

00:13:52.219 --> 00:13:59.099
In Medtronic, we usually need to do R validation after we have updated version of R. I don't

00:13:59.099 --> 00:14:05.500
know if JST has this requirement to do R validation for the submission work.

00:14:05.539 --> 00:14:06.539
Yeah.

00:14:06.539 --> 00:14:09.700
So, GSK, we do R validation.

00:14:09.700 --> 00:14:14.179
A lot of how we do R validation can actually be found on the R Validation Hub, which I

00:14:14.179 --> 00:14:22.500
think is part of the – is either a POSIT working group or is loosely related.

00:14:22.500 --> 00:14:30.500
So, how we do it is really kind of taken from there in terms of how we do it, the R Validation

00:14:30.500 --> 00:14:31.500
Hub.

00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:33.500
I can try to find the link off the –

00:14:33.500 --> 00:14:35.500
Oh, I'll share it for you right now.

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:36.500
Okay.

00:14:36.500 --> 00:14:37.500
Perfect.

00:14:37.500 --> 00:14:38.500
Yeah.

00:14:38.500 --> 00:14:39.500
So, that's –

00:14:39.500 --> 00:14:40.500
Connor beat me to it.

00:14:40.500 --> 00:14:41.500
Thanks, Connor.

00:14:41.500 --> 00:14:42.500
There you go.

00:14:42.500 --> 00:14:43.500
So, yeah.

00:14:43.500 --> 00:14:44.500
So, we generally do that.

00:14:44.500 --> 00:14:50.539
We were a – we, being GSK, were a strong participant in figuring out how to do it.

00:14:50.539 --> 00:14:55.739
And then we worked with basically our QA department to make sure that we're checking all the boxes

00:14:55.739 --> 00:15:02.539
that we need to hit in order to say that, yes, we believe that this is validated.

00:15:02.580 --> 00:15:07.380
So, for those who are not in the pharma industry, maybe I'll explain what validation means because

00:15:07.380 --> 00:15:10.539
it's kind of like a – it's an interesting problem.

00:15:10.539 --> 00:15:19.260
So, within a biostats organization, you basically have two things that you need to accomplish

00:15:19.260 --> 00:15:22.539
to move assets or drugs through the pipeline.

00:15:22.539 --> 00:15:29.780
Basically, one, can you tell what – can you trust the efficacy of a drug and can you

00:15:29.780 --> 00:15:33.219
trust the safety of a drug or an asset?

00:15:33.219 --> 00:15:40.059
And how you do that is you write statistical code in order to be able to prove that, yes,

00:15:40.059 --> 00:15:45.380
we trust these statistical tests that we've written.

00:15:45.380 --> 00:15:51.299
In order to do that, you need to do something that's called validation for your software,

00:15:51.299 --> 00:15:56.700
which is essentially to say we have tested the software and we believe that all the outputs

00:15:56.700 --> 00:16:02.099
from this software is correct.

00:16:02.099 --> 00:16:07.700
How you do validation is defined by the organization, but it's really important for you to be able

00:16:07.700 --> 00:16:09.820
to trust your software.

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:16.739
So, there's a lot of testing that goes into place in order to get that level of confidence

00:16:16.739 --> 00:16:22.219
within an organization that says, yes, this software can be trusted.

00:16:22.219 --> 00:16:24.700
And there's different nuances for how you do the testing.

00:16:24.700 --> 00:16:30.460
So, for example, if you're using ggplot2 for creating outputs of graphics, things like

00:16:30.460 --> 00:16:37.580
that, you can generally test it through code coverage as well as basically doing a couple

00:16:37.580 --> 00:16:44.020
simple simulations and saying, okay, does it actually create the output that we would

00:16:44.020 --> 00:16:52.859
expect if you were to put it – basically create that output?

00:16:52.859 --> 00:16:53.979
So, there's that.

00:16:53.979 --> 00:16:57.460
But then there's also output – there's validation from a statistical correctness

00:16:57.460 --> 00:16:58.460
point of view.

00:16:58.460 --> 00:17:04.859
So, for example, if we're writing a piece – a package to do linear regression or doing

00:17:04.859 --> 00:17:09.660
a linear regression – or using a package for linear regression, how do you test for

00:17:09.660 --> 00:17:11.260
that statistical correctness?

00:17:11.260 --> 00:17:16.219
And that's a little bit more of a thornier problem to figure out, but it tends to require

00:17:16.219 --> 00:17:20.300
like a lot of different simulations, things like that, in order to be able to say, yes,

00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:23.900
from a statistical correctness point of view, we trust this piece of software.

