00:17:57.900 --> 00:18:01.619
So, when you validate – I mean, where are you all hosting your R?

00:18:01.619 --> 00:18:02.619
Is it like Workbench?

00:18:02.619 --> 00:18:03.939
Do you run it in the cloud?

00:18:03.939 --> 00:18:06.540
Are these like Docker containers, local machines?

00:18:06.540 --> 00:18:08.300
Like, what do you do for that?

00:18:08.300 --> 00:18:09.300
Yeah.

00:18:09.300 --> 00:18:15.339
So, what we do is we have it – we host it on Workbench, and what we do basically is

00:18:15.339 --> 00:18:20.140
we create what's known as a frozen R environment, which is basically an environment that has

00:18:20.140 --> 00:18:24.739
a set number of packages that we have gone through the validation process with and said,

00:18:24.739 --> 00:18:26.459
yes, we trust these packages.

00:18:26.459 --> 00:18:32.979
So, then what we do is then we create basically a frozen R – I don't know.

00:18:32.979 --> 00:18:39.140
It's not truly a container, but basically an execution script where we can then basically

00:18:39.140 --> 00:18:43.060
just take and install that in any system that we choose.

00:18:43.180 --> 00:18:45.180
So, the goal is to make it system agnostic.

00:18:45.180 --> 00:18:54.020
So, for example, if we want to install it in like in Posit Workbench on our own internal,

00:18:54.020 --> 00:18:58.900
you know, our own internal RStudio cloud environment, we could do that.

00:18:58.900 --> 00:19:06.939
If we want to do it on, I don't know, pick your data science Workbench, Domino, I don't

00:19:06.939 --> 00:19:11.099
know, whatever, different things like that, you're able to do it, but trying to make it

00:19:11.099 --> 00:19:12.099
system agnostic.

00:19:12.099 --> 00:19:13.099
That's cool.

00:19:13.099 --> 00:19:14.099
Thanks.

00:19:14.099 --> 00:19:17.619
Yeah, I mean, there's like two levels to the validation.

00:19:17.619 --> 00:19:22.060
It always seems like validating the packages inside of R and then validating the installation

00:19:22.060 --> 00:19:23.060
of R itself.

00:19:23.060 --> 00:19:28.540
And that latter one is the one that, you know, we've had the most challenges with, you know,

00:19:28.540 --> 00:19:33.780
how do you prove that R is actually R, is sort of the philosophy, the spirit of what

00:19:33.780 --> 00:19:38.579
FDA wants to see, and we find that surprisingly difficult.

00:19:38.579 --> 00:19:39.939
I think they're coming around to it, though.

00:19:39.939 --> 00:19:43.859
If you see some of the talks that they've given in terms of like the R adoption series

00:19:43.859 --> 00:19:47.619
and things like that, I think they're, and also, I mean, frankly, if you just look at

00:19:47.619 --> 00:19:53.979
like statistical master's programs and things like that, like R is now kind of the tool

00:19:53.979 --> 00:19:54.979
to use.

00:19:54.979 --> 00:20:00.660
So I think from like a, call it a culture point of view, I think that's changing pretty,

00:20:00.660 --> 00:20:03.339
pretty rapidly just because of just how the workforce is changing.

