I think both are used when it gets published.

00:21:27.020 --> 00:21:33.219
PackRat manages the package versions and does the uploading, so basically, it's kind of

00:21:33.219 --> 00:21:39.660
like a docker light for your packages that makes sure that all of the revs are there,

00:21:39.660 --> 00:21:46.020
and it keeps a library in the background and makes sure that everything's synced up.

00:21:46.020 --> 00:21:53.739
And I would imagine RM is used as well, but I don't know the technical details of that.

00:21:53.739 --> 00:21:58.020
One nice thing about publishing Connect2Connect is I don't have to, it just does it on the

00:21:58.020 --> 00:21:59.020
background.

00:21:59.020 --> 00:22:04.780
But if I was writing it myself, yeah, I'm sure you'd have to use a combination of both

00:22:04.780 --> 00:22:08.020
if you weren't publishing Direct2Connect.

