But Lisa, I see you had a question a bit earlier about being outside of PhRMA and how things

00:22:20.660 --> 00:22:21.660
might relate.

00:22:21.780 --> 00:22:23.780
Do you want to ask that?

00:22:23.780 --> 00:22:30.420
Yeah, I mean, I think I'm both curious about just like sort of learning the PhRMA lingo,

00:22:30.420 --> 00:22:35.099
which has, like every industry, a lot of abbreviations to it.

00:22:35.099 --> 00:22:40.180
And then just really also, you know, sort of trying to understand that whole process

00:22:40.180 --> 00:22:46.380
and think about how those same ideas might, you know, even though maybe I'm in an industry

00:22:46.380 --> 00:22:51.819
that's less regulated, how some of those ideas might want to steal some of those because

00:22:51.819 --> 00:22:55.020
it might just be good practice in general.

00:22:55.020 --> 00:22:58.660
So just kind of where to, good places to start learning.

00:22:58.660 --> 00:23:02.979
And I already saw the, our PhRMA conference posted out there.

00:23:02.979 --> 00:23:05.500
So any other ideas would be great.

00:23:05.500 --> 00:23:16.219
I think at the core of the PhRMA world is basically, can you reproduce your outputs

00:23:16.219 --> 00:23:19.699
and can you trust and verify those outputs?

00:23:19.699 --> 00:23:26.300
So like you could learn, you could learn like the PhRMA lingo if you want it.

00:23:26.300 --> 00:23:31.660
But I think the core thing is like, do you, can you figure out how to create reproducible

00:23:31.660 --> 00:23:33.260
data pipelines essentially?

00:23:33.260 --> 00:23:39.300
And I think if you are able to do that through different methods, as well as using sort of

00:23:39.300 --> 00:23:43.060
like potentially like RMF in terms of like how to manage your environment and things

00:23:43.060 --> 00:23:47.500
like that, I think you actually will, you actually know more, like that's essentially

00:23:47.500 --> 00:23:54.420
the core of what is PhRMA principles essentially is how do you reproduce, how do you make sure

00:23:54.420 --> 00:23:59.500
that it's reproducible and how do you make sure that you can trust and verify your outputs?

00:23:59.500 --> 00:24:00.939
And I think that's kind of the core.

00:24:00.939 --> 00:24:01.939
Awesome.

