00:24:46.020 --> 00:24:53.099
There was another question a bit earlier, and I'm not finding it specific exactly, but

00:24:53.099 --> 00:24:57.900
the question was, Ben, can you give us a little bit more background around your role too and

00:24:57.979 --> 00:24:59.979
what your team looks like?

00:24:59.979 --> 00:25:01.939
Yeah, sure.

00:25:01.939 --> 00:25:10.380
So my role is really, I like to split it up into, call it four pillars of responsibility.

00:25:10.380 --> 00:25:18.020
I have a team that focuses on building sort of end-to-end applications for trying to gather

00:25:18.020 --> 00:25:22.859
insights about data related to either clinical trials or some of our business partners outside

00:25:22.859 --> 00:25:25.859
of biostatistics.

00:25:25.859 --> 00:25:32.619
One I can give a shout out to is called the BPH tool, which is an externally facing tool

00:25:32.619 --> 00:25:42.859
on how to treat a certain urological, it's not disease, but called symptoms.

00:25:42.859 --> 00:25:45.099
So I'll put that in the chat.

00:25:45.099 --> 00:25:47.979
But we built that using Shiny.

00:25:47.979 --> 00:25:49.780
It's linked to like scientific manuscripts.

00:25:49.780 --> 00:25:56.180
And so one of the things that we try to do now is when we submit a manuscript, try to

00:25:56.180 --> 00:26:01.540
either submit a interactive tool or enhanced graphics with the manuscript in order to make

00:26:01.540 --> 00:26:06.060
it easier for people to understand the data.

00:26:06.060 --> 00:26:07.060
So that's one team.

00:26:07.060 --> 00:26:10.500
I have a team that focuses on building like open source packages.

00:26:10.500 --> 00:26:16.660
One of the big things we're looking at now is like Bayesian statistics.

00:26:16.660 --> 00:26:23.420
And I have a third team that's focused on doing basically R training as well as R enablement.

00:26:23.420 --> 00:26:27.939
So we have a program called Accelerate R, which is a group of agile, it's an agile pod

00:26:27.939 --> 00:26:33.420
of data scientists and R programmers that go basically study to study, sit with them

00:26:33.420 --> 00:26:41.579
for nine to 10 weeks, train them on the use of R, and then basically leave after those

00:26:41.579 --> 00:26:42.579
10 weeks.

00:26:42.579 --> 00:26:46.500
But really set up those studies to be able to use R effectively.

00:26:47.339 --> 00:26:51.739
And then I have a fourth kind of like, kind of pillar of responsibility, which is focused

00:26:51.739 --> 00:26:55.819
on being engaged in like data science working groups, and different things like that in

00:26:55.819 --> 00:27:02.180
order to be able to, to talk about R as well as be able to have a kind of industry standard

00:27:02.180 --> 00:27:06.819
for how to use R for different ways for clinical, for clinical trials.

00:27:06.819 --> 00:27:11.300
And we talk about things that, you know, might sound silly, like, you know, how do you round

00:27:11.300 --> 00:27:17.540
in R versus SAS and Python, but being able to talk very confidently about those differences

00:27:17.540 --> 00:27:22.660
and why you might get differences in results is a pretty crucial aspect for our industry.

00:27:22.660 --> 00:27:29.859
I know you just mentioned the training piece, but I realized that's like a huge undertaking

00:27:29.859 --> 00:27:32.339
with so many different trainees.

00:27:32.339 --> 00:27:35.579
And I was wondering, how do you scale that training out?

00:27:35.579 --> 00:27:39.060
I think when we talked, you said that there's like 800 trainees?

00:27:39.420 --> 00:27:46.180
Yeah, so within Biostats, GSK Biostats, we're about 900 people.

00:27:46.180 --> 00:27:54.500
So what we started to do initially was having just open in-person as well as like virtual

00:27:54.500 --> 00:28:01.859
trainings with R. So like, I think we got to the point where 80% of Biostats took an

00:28:01.859 --> 00:28:08.979
introduction to tidyverse R training, which is like, you know, 80% of 900 is like right

00:28:08.979 --> 00:28:11.140
around 700, 720, something like that.

00:28:11.780 --> 00:28:18.420
And what we were finding was people just weren't uptaking the training and using it on clinical

00:28:18.420 --> 00:28:18.900
trials.

00:28:18.900 --> 00:28:23.859
And the big reason we found out was because you would take the training and then you wouldn't

00:28:23.859 --> 00:28:29.459
actually use the, you wouldn't use R until like 12 or 18 months later.

00:28:29.459 --> 00:28:33.300
So what we ended up doing was deciding like, all right, let's just put R training as on

00:28:33.300 --> 00:28:34.020
demand.

00:28:34.020 --> 00:28:38.500
Like, I'm never going to write a better like intro to tidyverse training than, you know,

00:28:38.500 --> 00:28:41.300
either Hadley's written or someone else has written online.

00:28:41.300 --> 00:28:45.859
Let's just make it all on demand when you want to do it and focus purely on like support

00:28:45.859 --> 00:28:46.500
and mentoring.

00:28:46.500 --> 00:28:53.060
So what we do is we have this like small group of people and they go, you know, basically

00:28:53.060 --> 00:28:57.859
study to study whoever wants to use R at that period of time and we work with them.

00:28:58.500 --> 00:29:03.939
And the goal is basically train that study team up and create them into like champions

00:29:03.939 --> 00:29:08.339
and then also give them the confidence to be able to go to other studies and help provide

00:29:08.339 --> 00:29:10.260
guidance as well.

00:29:10.260 --> 00:29:14.180
So we do it through that kind of support and mentoring, but we also have like big community

00:29:14.180 --> 00:29:18.339
engagement through different like open forums where people can ask questions, things like

00:29:18.339 --> 00:29:18.900
that.

00:29:18.900 --> 00:29:24.099
So it's really focused on like spending less time on creating materials for training and

00:29:24.099 --> 00:29:28.260
documentation and more time on figuring out like, all right, how do we actually do support

00:29:28.260 --> 00:29:35.699
and mentoring as well as get feedback to build tools that actually will help our users for

00:29:35.699 --> 00:29:37.939
actually using R on clinical trials.

00:29:38.739 --> 00:29:40.979
And Ben, I see you have a question in the chat.

00:29:40.979 --> 00:29:41.780
You want to jump in here?

00:29:43.060 --> 00:29:51.300
Yeah, I was curious, Ben, if you have other cross disciplines across GSK as it's so large.

00:29:51.300 --> 00:29:55.380
I mean, obviously you have a large enough group you're working with to try and ramp

00:29:55.380 --> 00:30:00.339
them up, but it seems like there could be other opportunities that would enhance the

00:30:00.339 --> 00:30:02.420
efficiency of the tools and so on and so forth.

00:30:03.699 --> 00:30:05.780
Yeah, there's lots of different data science groups.

00:30:05.780 --> 00:30:10.260
So like I feel like, you know, sometimes you just like stumble upon them because I think

00:30:10.260 --> 00:30:15.619
GSK, I think we're like 100,000 people or something like that, maybe a little bit less.

00:30:16.180 --> 00:30:21.459
And so you're just like, you're just like, you just stumble upon them.

00:30:23.219 --> 00:30:25.619
For Biostats, we're pretty large, luckily.

00:30:25.619 --> 00:30:28.420
So we work a lot with our business partners.

00:30:29.380 --> 00:30:34.099
And the reason why we work with them is like, because Biostats really focuses on moving

00:30:34.099 --> 00:30:38.500
assets through the pipeline, we have like direct impacts on like HR or finance.

00:30:38.500 --> 00:30:44.099
So like we have those connections that we do, but like we have a whole like AI group

00:30:44.099 --> 00:30:48.020
that's focused on like computational biology and computational chemistry and different

00:30:48.020 --> 00:30:48.739
things like that.

00:30:48.739 --> 00:30:55.060
So there's like lots of different data science groups within GSK.

00:30:56.339 --> 00:31:00.260
Some of them work across departments, but a lot of them tend to work like within their

00:31:00.260 --> 00:31:06.020
own department because they're so hyper focused on like specific problems that they're

00:31:06.020 --> 00:31:06.660
trying to solve.

00:31:07.300 --> 00:31:12.979
I was talking to someone at the conference who works in pharma and hearing about some

00:31:13.060 --> 00:31:18.099
of like the different finance use cases within pharma, which I wouldn't initially think

00:31:18.099 --> 00:31:18.979
about as well.

00:31:19.459 --> 00:31:20.020
Yeah.

00:31:20.020 --> 00:31:24.180
It's cool to hear about all the different data science teams across companies.

00:31:26.979 --> 00:31:30.979
This was actually a Slido question from your conference talk, which I thought, because

00:31:30.979 --> 00:31:33.060
we didn't get to it, we could cover it here.

00:31:34.099 --> 00:31:40.660
But it was, how do you think about redefining the way that people see themselves, like

00:31:40.660 --> 00:31:45.540
helping statisticians see themselves as programmers and using Git, for example?

00:31:47.699 --> 00:31:48.180
Yeah.

00:31:48.180 --> 00:31:51.619
So I actually don't believe in having people redefine themselves.

00:31:52.500 --> 00:31:59.619
I actually think about how do you help someone like learn a tool or add a tool to their

00:31:59.619 --> 00:32:03.780
toolkit in order to like enhance the way that they're working?

00:32:03.780 --> 00:32:10.660
Because at the end of the day, you are not going to turn like a statistician into a

00:32:10.660 --> 00:32:14.660
programmer or a computer scientist or things like that unless they really want to become

00:32:14.660 --> 00:32:14.900
one.

00:32:16.020 --> 00:32:19.619
So I think the goal is like you don't actually try to redefine them.

00:32:19.619 --> 00:32:31.699
I think you try to help them add tools to their toolkit in order to be able to use it

00:32:31.699 --> 00:32:33.060
in order to enhance their work.

00:32:33.060 --> 00:32:40.420
So like teaching like a statistician Git, like you have to explain why it's important

00:32:40.420 --> 00:32:45.939
for them to know, you know, kind of the hit by the bus rule, if anyone's familiar with

00:32:45.939 --> 00:32:46.180
that.

00:32:47.780 --> 00:32:48.099
But yeah.

00:32:48.099 --> 00:32:51.380
It's time to use the what if you won the lottery.

00:32:51.380 --> 00:32:53.859
Or yeah, what if you were hit by a bus.

00:32:53.859 --> 00:32:55.780
Yeah, that's a better way to put it, I guess.

00:32:56.500 --> 00:33:01.060
But yeah, so like I think it's more focused on like, how do you help people add and not

00:33:01.060 --> 00:33:02.260
necessarily redefine?

00:33:03.140 --> 00:33:03.780
Absolutely.

00:33:04.819 --> 00:33:12.020
And is this the training initiative, something that's kind of come from the top at GSK?

00:33:12.020 --> 00:33:13.459
Or how was it first rolled out?

00:33:14.819 --> 00:33:19.459
Yeah, so I mean, it was more it wasn't necessary.

00:33:19.459 --> 00:33:21.060
It wasn't really rolled out from the top.

00:33:21.060 --> 00:33:26.260
It was more like, we got the blessing from the leadership team that says, hey, we want

00:33:26.260 --> 00:33:28.500
to try something pretty different.

00:33:30.260 --> 00:33:31.780
Are you okay with this approach?

00:33:32.339 --> 00:33:33.859
And got the thumbs up.

00:33:33.859 --> 00:33:41.859
And so we got the thumbs up to say, yeah, go and go and try this new this new way to

00:33:41.859 --> 00:33:45.780
train focus less on this on the classes focus more on support and mentoring.

00:33:45.780 --> 00:33:48.020
And that's how we were able to do it.

00:33:48.020 --> 00:33:52.900
So it was luckily we were given the freedom and the latitude to be able to try something

00:33:52.900 --> 00:33:53.140
new.

00:33:53.140 --> 00:33:58.420
And, you know, in the spirit of agile, fail fast if it didn't work, but it has worked

00:33:58.420 --> 00:33:58.900
pretty well.

00:33:58.900 --> 00:34:02.339
So luckily, it wasn't something that had to be top down driven.

00:34:02.339 --> 00:34:07.300
And I think it's a model that could be utilized pretty much in any organization.

00:34:08.979 --> 00:34:13.060
Because really, all you need is like people who are passionate about are and willing to

00:34:13.060 --> 00:34:15.939
spend some time to do that, that support and training.

00:34:16.979 --> 00:34:17.379
So yeah.

00:34:18.100 --> 00:34:23.620
I see like a pretty big conversation happening in the chat around rounding.

00:34:23.620 --> 00:34:29.620
And can somebody explain to me, I've heard of this and like how numbers can be different

00:34:29.620 --> 00:34:34.419
and SAS versus R, but I would love to understand a little bit more of what that means.

00:34:35.139 --> 00:34:37.139
I see a bunch of blanks being here.

00:34:39.060 --> 00:34:41.699
In general, someone someone correct me if I mess this up.

00:34:42.419 --> 00:34:48.500
But in general, computer science has adopted the strategy that if you have something that

00:34:48.500 --> 00:34:54.260
ends in 0.5, like 2.5, you round the even numbers down.

00:34:55.139 --> 00:34:58.500
So like 2.5 becomes two and the odd ones round up.

00:34:58.500 --> 00:35:00.500
So 3.5 becomes four.

00:35:01.780 --> 00:35:05.620
And so what that does is on average, if you have like a whole bunch of numbers that end

00:35:05.620 --> 00:35:10.500
in 0.5, then the rounding up and down like on average doesn't really matter.

00:35:11.060 --> 00:35:14.739
SAS, on the other hand, is the only language that will round everything in 0.5 up.

00:35:15.699 --> 00:35:20.659
So if you had a whole bunch of numbers and you rounded them all, you would actually get

00:35:20.659 --> 00:35:25.300
an average that is higher than the true average was because everything got rounded up instead

00:35:25.300 --> 00:35:26.979
of like every other one getting rounded up.

00:35:27.620 --> 00:35:34.100
And it's a very annoying nuance for submissions to like FDA or sponsors or investigators when

00:35:34.100 --> 00:35:38.340
they're used to seeing SAS outputs and everything that's 0.5 being rounded up.

00:35:38.340 --> 00:35:39.459
They start to question that.

00:35:39.459 --> 00:35:45.699
And indeed, at the FDA, if you submit something in R, you might get a mismatch in SAS because

00:35:45.699 --> 00:35:46.659
of that rounding problem.

00:35:46.659 --> 00:35:47.300
It's a weird one.

00:35:48.100 --> 00:35:52.659
Do you have to write like custom functions to do R rounding like SAS in order to get

00:35:52.659 --> 00:35:56.260
around that or just kind of explain it away via differences?

00:35:56.899 --> 00:35:58.100
Yeah, those do exist.

00:35:58.100 --> 00:36:02.500
And Stephanie in here shared a really good resource that looks like some packages and

00:36:02.500 --> 00:36:04.580
other people developed around this idea.

00:36:04.580 --> 00:36:05.300
But yeah, for sure.

00:36:05.860 --> 00:36:08.419
There are custom functions that we sometimes write.

00:36:08.419 --> 00:36:12.100
If they really just insist that everything 0.5 rounds up, then we go, yeah, OK.

00:36:12.979 --> 00:36:13.699
And we just note it.

00:36:14.500 --> 00:36:16.659
Thank you for that explanation.

00:36:18.260 --> 00:36:22.020
Yeah, sometimes it's like if something's been said like enough times, it's like, do

00:36:22.020 --> 00:36:24.260
I pretend that I know what that actually means?

00:36:24.260 --> 00:36:25.939
Or do we just stop and ask?

00:36:27.540 --> 00:36:29.939
Catherine, I see you had a question here in the chat.

00:36:29.939 --> 00:36:30.659
Do you want to jump in?

00:36:31.620 --> 00:36:36.820
Yeah, you've mentioned that you've switched kind of the way that you're training from

00:36:36.820 --> 00:36:39.219
a previous method and that it's been successful.

00:36:39.939 --> 00:36:42.179
But how are you measuring that success?

00:36:43.459 --> 00:36:46.739
We're currently rolling out like a data science mentorship program and trying to

00:36:46.739 --> 00:36:51.540
figure out how do we measure how successful we've been at mentoring this person when we

00:36:51.540 --> 00:36:57.219
don't necessarily want to turn them into a machine learning engineer or a programmer

00:36:57.219 --> 00:36:57.540
or something.

00:36:57.540 --> 00:36:59.620
We just want them to be better data scientists.

00:37:00.419 --> 00:37:01.459
And data professionals.

00:37:02.739 --> 00:37:09.860
Yeah, so for us specifically, we're pretty it's it's we try to keep it very simple,

00:37:09.860 --> 00:37:14.739
which is basically like how many outputs are we creating with R and is that number

00:37:14.739 --> 00:37:15.620
increasing?

00:37:15.620 --> 00:37:19.379
And if the answer is yes, then we're hitting our metrics essentially.

00:37:19.379 --> 00:37:24.419
Or is the number of clinical trials that we want to use R in some part of increasing?

00:37:24.419 --> 00:37:26.179
Then the answer is yes.

00:37:26.179 --> 00:37:33.780
We believe that we are we are hitting our our our tracking or metrics in order to say

00:37:33.780 --> 00:37:36.739
yes, our enablement is is increasing.

00:37:37.300 --> 00:37:39.939
If you're talking about like, how do you make someone?

00:37:41.379 --> 00:37:42.260
How do you make some?

00:37:42.260 --> 00:37:46.899
How do you track if someone is improving their skills?

00:37:47.540 --> 00:37:53.060
To me, that's more like a development plan kind of point of view at an individual level.

00:37:53.620 --> 00:37:55.860
But I think it's really hard.

00:37:55.860 --> 00:38:00.739
I think you can only do it in terms of in terms if you really want to track, I think

00:38:00.739 --> 00:38:07.139
it has to be sort of like at an aggregate output level and not necessarily did this

00:38:07.139 --> 00:38:12.580
person like comprehend unless it's like at a development or a career or personal development

00:38:12.580 --> 00:38:12.899
level.

00:38:12.899 --> 00:38:13.620
If that makes sense.

00:38:14.179 --> 00:38:17.379
Yeah, I think that makes a lot of sense, especially given that your team's goal is

00:38:17.379 --> 00:38:18.179
R enablement.

00:38:18.179 --> 00:38:21.379
That's something that's fairly straightforward to track.

00:38:22.340 --> 00:38:25.300
Are we seeing a higher use of R?

00:38:25.300 --> 00:38:29.540
Yeah, we're doing the professional development part was was a lot harder.

00:38:29.540 --> 00:38:33.379
We had, you know, a couple ideas, but really, you know, one of those things is are they

00:38:33.379 --> 00:38:34.899
using it now?

00:38:34.899 --> 00:38:38.020
And like, that's something that we're that we're tracking as part of that, too.

00:38:39.540 --> 00:38:44.820
Yeah, that gets really hard having gone through like those wars with like trying to teach

00:38:44.820 --> 00:38:50.020
people how to use it like it's it's the steepest learning curve that I think I've ever

00:38:50.020 --> 00:38:52.739
encountered with with with teams.

00:38:52.739 --> 00:38:54.580
It just it's really, really tough.

00:38:55.459 --> 00:38:59.939
And there's just like so many points of friction, just like when you get your first merge

00:38:59.939 --> 00:39:01.860
conflict and you just don't know what to do.

00:39:01.860 --> 00:39:06.419
And it seems like the world just like will not let you merge your, you know, your branches

00:39:06.419 --> 00:39:09.459
together like it is a really, really tough thing.

00:39:09.459 --> 00:39:12.659
So you just unprotect your branches and merge them anyway.

00:39:12.659 --> 00:39:13.219
It's fine.

00:39:14.419 --> 00:39:18.179
Yeah, but then you got to explain it to someone later on reproducibility, right?

00:39:18.179 --> 00:39:22.179
So I see Rebecca had a question.

00:39:22.179 --> 00:39:25.139
There's a star, so I'll read it, but it kind of expands on this.

00:39:25.139 --> 00:39:29.459
But how are you demonstrating or showing that evidence for it working?

00:39:30.179 --> 00:39:35.620
I guess to expand on this, are you presenting this to anybody as well?

00:39:38.899 --> 00:39:44.340
What specifically in terms of I think about to expand on like how you're measuring or

00:39:44.340 --> 00:39:46.899
tracking the success against the previous method?

00:39:48.260 --> 00:39:54.979
Yeah, I mean, I don't think we I mean, we're not trying to get to a world where R replaces

00:39:54.979 --> 00:39:55.459
SAS.

00:39:55.459 --> 00:40:00.020
We want to live in a world where you can select the tool that you want to use to create your

00:40:00.020 --> 00:40:00.979
outputs.

00:40:00.979 --> 00:40:11.139
So if our goal is to make R a primary programming language or a tool that can be used, we should

00:40:11.139 --> 00:40:16.340
be and there's an interest and we should be able to see increase of the use of R.

00:40:16.340 --> 00:40:21.780
So like I don't look at it as like as a I look at it as like you have options and we

00:40:21.780 --> 00:40:27.540
want to make sure those options are being utilized and not like how do I get R usage

00:40:27.540 --> 00:40:31.139
from, you know, 10 percent to 100 percent within my organization.

00:40:31.699 --> 00:40:33.699
Thank you, Kevin.

00:40:33.699 --> 00:40:36.020
I see you had a question around the cultural barriers.

00:40:36.020 --> 00:40:36.659
Want to jump in?

00:40:37.379 --> 00:40:38.419
Yeah, sure.

00:40:38.419 --> 00:40:42.260
Yeah, I think you spoke a little bit to this, but but I was just curious if you could elaborate

00:40:42.260 --> 00:40:47.379
more on how you kind of dealt with cultural barriers to adopting open source, you know,

00:40:47.379 --> 00:40:49.780
in pharma, especially like, yeah, it's a regulated industry.

00:40:49.780 --> 00:40:55.939
And and I almost want to frame it like like was it more helpful to show like the efficacy

00:40:55.939 --> 00:40:56.659
of open source?

00:40:56.659 --> 00:40:59.300
Or is it more important to show the safety of it?

00:40:59.300 --> 00:41:01.939
You know, like or there's both kind of important, you know what I mean?

00:41:02.580 --> 00:41:03.540
Yeah, yeah.

00:41:03.540 --> 00:41:12.500
So the the big thing that actually was the major major way that we broke a lot of ground

00:41:12.500 --> 00:41:14.739
in terms of open source was visualizations.

00:41:15.300 --> 00:41:21.699
So because one of the big things that R does so well is is ggplot and being able to create

00:41:21.699 --> 00:41:25.459
like awesome visualizations, you know, with data.

00:41:25.459 --> 00:41:29.780
And that was something that like SAS really, really struggled with.

00:41:29.780 --> 00:41:34.899
And so the wedge that we actually figured out in order to be able to start having the

00:41:34.899 --> 00:41:39.459
open source conversation was like, look at all these cool like visualizations and look

00:41:39.459 --> 00:41:45.620
how easy it is to make these visualizations compared to like other other programming languages.

00:41:46.419 --> 00:41:54.500
Why don't we like start looking at open source as like a way to be able to to you to basically

00:41:54.500 --> 00:41:55.699
use tools successfully?

00:41:56.260 --> 00:41:58.500
And then a lot of things happen.

00:41:58.500 --> 00:42:03.540
But I think the big another thing that really has broken through cultural barriers has been

00:42:03.540 --> 00:42:09.620
there's a really, really strong industry call it collaboration called like the farm reverse

00:42:09.620 --> 00:42:12.020
where different and different companies.

00:42:12.659 --> 00:42:18.899
So like Roche, GSK, Novartis, J&J, like all these different companies are creating open

00:42:18.899 --> 00:42:23.860
source packages for the clinical trial development pipeline.

00:42:23.860 --> 00:42:28.500
So like if you can set if you as an industry can agree upon, like we all trust these open

00:42:28.500 --> 00:42:29.139
source tools.

00:42:30.100 --> 00:42:34.260
It really kind of helps to break down those cultural barriers about like, why should I

00:42:34.260 --> 00:42:35.780
use this open source tool?

00:42:35.780 --> 00:42:40.260
And it's it's really easy to say, like, well, we want to use it because, you know, Roche

00:42:40.260 --> 00:42:46.419
is using it or we've developed it with Roche and with, you know, insert other pharma company.

00:42:46.419 --> 00:42:49.699
And you can say we we we helped create it.

00:42:49.699 --> 00:42:50.500
We should trust it.

00:42:51.219 --> 00:42:55.379
And so I think that has been one of the things that has helped with those cultural barriers.

00:42:57.620 --> 00:42:59.139
Just one follow up.

00:42:59.139 --> 00:43:03.379
Did you ever hit a wall where like there's some parts of the organization or some people,

00:43:03.379 --> 00:43:09.060
you know, some managers who just like can't get over the, you know, that that the validation

00:43:09.060 --> 00:43:11.540
or the kind of concerns about about open source?

00:43:11.540 --> 00:43:16.659
Or did you find you were able to pretty much break through it when you needed to?

00:43:16.659 --> 00:43:20.739
I think you can break through, but at the end of the day, like I tried to talk a little

00:43:20.739 --> 00:43:27.300
bit about earlier, like if people want to use their proprietary tool, fine, if it helps

00:43:27.300 --> 00:43:28.260
them do their work.

00:43:28.260 --> 00:43:31.780
Like at the end of the day, like all I care about is like, can you do your work and can

00:43:31.780 --> 00:43:35.860
you do your work in a timely manner and not have like bottlenecks with platforms?

00:43:35.860 --> 00:43:38.820
And if the answer is yes, then like, who cares?

00:43:38.820 --> 00:43:42.100
You know, if that's your preferred tool, that's where you like to spend your time, then like

00:43:42.100 --> 00:43:43.379
I'm not going to tell you differently.

00:43:44.100 --> 00:43:44.739
That makes sense.

00:43:44.739 --> 00:43:45.239
Thank you.

