But there was one anonymous question that was.

00:44:06.120 --> 00:44:12.439
When we sit, when we say like what the FDA wants to see, like, what does that actually

00:44:12.439 --> 00:44:13.080
mean?

00:44:13.080 --> 00:44:18.679
Like, did those statements come directly from FDA employees or where do people hear that

00:44:19.239 --> 00:44:24.840
in terms of, I mean, you could talk a little bit about the FDA in terms of like, I think

00:44:24.840 --> 00:44:26.600
there's like guidance on software.

00:44:26.600 --> 00:44:31.399
Like if I was Phil Boucher, I would like have the PDF up already on like what it is that

00:44:31.399 --> 00:44:31.899
you can use.

00:44:32.600 --> 00:44:38.360
But I think there's a lot of like when you submit something to an FDA or another regulatory

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:41.959
agency, it's like an open conversation and you have a conversation.

00:44:41.959 --> 00:44:45.639
And so it's not just like it's not a piece of homework where I have to submit this at

00:44:45.639 --> 00:44:47.719
midnight and then I get a grade.

00:44:47.719 --> 00:44:50.600
There's like an ongoing back and forth conversation that occurs.

00:44:51.159 --> 00:44:57.959
And so being able to being able to engage and have those conversations is where you

00:44:57.959 --> 00:45:02.439
learn exactly like what it is that, you know, is needed from a regulator.

00:45:02.439 --> 00:45:06.439
Now there's like expected standards and you know what standards it is that you have to

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:12.840
hit in terms of like having a successful submission or or ad hoc analysis or whatever it

00:45:12.840 --> 00:45:15.959
might be to be able to answer, you know, a scientific question.

00:45:16.760 --> 00:45:20.439
But it's not like I said, it's not a it's an ongoing conversation.

00:45:21.080 --> 00:45:24.520
It's not like a submit your homework and you and you hope you get a good grade.

00:45:25.639 --> 00:45:26.199
Thank you, Ben.

