It was like, no, this doesn't work on my machine.

00:47:06.199 --> 00:47:10.679
And then to Ben's point about it being conversation, they kind of had a conversation.

00:47:10.679 --> 00:47:11.320
They work through it.

00:47:11.320 --> 00:47:15.399
So I was wondering if you had any like, you know, just gut reactions about that talk,

00:47:15.399 --> 00:47:18.520
like any further commentary you might call you might want to add to what they showed.

00:47:18.840 --> 00:47:24.600
Yeah, there are two things that I really took away from that talk.

00:47:24.600 --> 00:47:28.439
One, it was a really similar story.

00:47:28.439 --> 00:47:32.919
We all are solving the same problem, albeit in our different ways, based off like our

00:47:32.919 --> 00:47:36.280
organizational culture or just organizational preferences.

00:47:37.959 --> 00:47:45.479
The big thing I took away from it actually is if we are going down the open source route

00:47:45.959 --> 00:47:52.040
in terms of R and different R packages, things like that, I think it's actually going to

00:47:52.040 --> 00:48:00.679
potentially create a stronger culture of open source tools because it seemed like the.

00:48:02.280 --> 00:48:07.560
And by that, I mean, I don't know if we're going to if specific companies will be able

00:48:07.560 --> 00:48:14.360
to have internal tools that only they can use because of the issues that Novo had with

00:48:14.520 --> 00:48:19.800
Novo had with using their own internal tools and trying to do a submission because of like,

00:48:20.360 --> 00:48:25.239
how do I get them to be able to install this package, which might not be available on CRAN?

00:48:25.239 --> 00:48:26.600
How do I be able to do this?

00:48:26.600 --> 00:48:30.679
So I think it actually one of the things that it's made me think a lot about is like,

00:48:31.239 --> 00:48:37.719
how much internally do we actually want to create because of like the hiccups that could

00:48:37.719 --> 00:48:40.919
cause in the actual submission process?

00:48:40.919 --> 00:48:47.879
And will that potentially result in like a stronger open source ecosystem because of just

00:48:47.879 --> 00:48:55.320
like just the making it easier in order to for regulators, whether it be FDA,

00:48:55.320 --> 00:48:58.760
EMA, Japan, whatever it might be to be able to use these tools?

00:48:59.560 --> 00:49:00.439
That's such a great answer.

00:49:00.439 --> 00:49:01.560
Yeah, I felt the same.

00:49:01.560 --> 00:49:04.679
There was that one part in their talk where they where they said, well, the solution was

00:49:04.679 --> 00:49:08.520
just we needed to open source everything and then the FDA was happy and I was like,

00:49:08.520 --> 00:49:10.040
oh, I didn't expect that.

00:49:10.040 --> 00:49:14.760
But it's almost like it's a good advisory tip for those of us developing internal packages

00:49:14.760 --> 00:49:21.159
at our companies like that may not be a sustainable journey in the future when we go to submit.

00:49:21.159 --> 00:49:21.399
Yeah.

00:49:21.399 --> 00:49:25.000
And I think the big thing that I have been thinking a lot about it is like the reason

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:28.360
why we've never encountered this, we being the pharma industry has never encountered

00:49:28.360 --> 00:49:31.479
this is because like, say, SAS is your tool of choice.

00:49:32.040 --> 00:49:36.919
Theoretically, SAS is the same from one organization to the other.

00:49:36.919 --> 00:49:41.239
And I keep harping on this, so I'm sorry, but like reproducibility is key.

00:49:41.239 --> 00:49:45.959
So if it exists in two or if your proprietary tool exists in two organizations in the same

00:49:46.760 --> 00:49:52.600
version X, Y, Z, then you kind of have to make sure that that's guaranteed if you're

00:49:52.600 --> 00:49:53.879
using open source tools.

00:49:53.879 --> 00:49:59.239
And like from a philosophical point of view, that probably means we have to open source

00:49:59.239 --> 00:50:05.479
more to make sure that everyone has access and we don't have these like very secret internal

00:50:05.479 --> 00:50:07.800
tools that cause issues with submissions.

00:50:08.520 --> 00:50:09.000
Thank you.

00:50:10.600 --> 00:50:17.320
Ben, a question I love to get to ask people is about career advice they've received over

00:50:17.320 --> 00:50:19.879
the course of their career or have given.

00:50:19.879 --> 00:50:21.639
Do you have something that stands out?

00:50:22.360 --> 00:50:22.919
Oh, man.

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:28.760
I think the thing that always stuck with me is it's OK to say no.

00:50:30.199 --> 00:50:34.280
Like you should be ruthlessly prioritizing your time and trying to work on things you're

00:50:34.280 --> 00:50:35.479
passionate about.

00:50:35.479 --> 00:50:40.600
So it's OK to say no to certain things if you are the wrong fit.

00:50:41.320 --> 00:50:45.879
It's also if you think about like your brand management, it's sometimes nice to be wanted.

00:50:45.879 --> 00:50:49.399
So saying no sometimes is good for that brand management.

00:50:50.280 --> 00:50:56.199
So I think being comfortable with the word no and is really important.

00:50:56.199 --> 00:51:01.320
The other thing and I think is really important or the other piece of advice that was given

00:51:01.320 --> 00:51:05.000
to me and I try to live by this value is like be radically transparent.

00:51:06.120 --> 00:51:13.719
So meaning no matter what, just be like just no such thing as like, you know, holding cards

00:51:13.719 --> 00:51:17.159
close to your chest, basically say like, here's what I got.

00:51:17.159 --> 00:51:17.800
What do you have?

00:51:18.679 --> 00:51:23.239
And really focus on being able to have those open and honest conversations, which I think

00:51:23.800 --> 00:51:27.320
leads to greater vulnerability, which is like how you make connections with people

00:51:27.800 --> 00:51:33.239
and really are able to be empathetic with people and trying to understand their problems.

00:51:33.239 --> 00:51:40.360
So I think being able to say no, but also and also being able to be radically transparent

00:51:40.360 --> 00:51:45.800
is really crucial work advice that people that a lot of mentors have given me in the past.

00:51:46.520 --> 00:51:47.239
Absolutely.

00:51:47.800 --> 00:51:49.800
Thank you so much for sharing that.

