00:52:11.639 --> 00:52:16.760
I know, like in your role, you get to connect with so many different teams through training

00:52:16.760 --> 00:52:23.560
and education, and I'm I'm curious how that's helped you in your role and how you build

00:52:23.560 --> 00:52:27.639
these relationships with people and they maintain those relationships.

00:52:28.600 --> 00:52:36.120
Yeah, I really like it because I'm able to understand more about like what do people

00:52:36.120 --> 00:52:37.080
what are people facing?

00:52:38.040 --> 00:52:42.439
And one of the things that I've learned is like every.

00:52:44.840 --> 00:52:49.000
Or one thing, one learning I've had from it is like no one's trying to do a bad job.

00:52:49.959 --> 00:52:55.239
It's just there's so many things that are going on in life that you have to people require

00:52:55.239 --> 00:52:57.239
like certain different levels of support.

00:52:57.239 --> 00:52:58.120
They all want to try.

00:52:58.760 --> 00:53:00.360
They all want to do the new cool thing.

00:53:00.360 --> 00:53:02.919
It's just everyone's at different stages.

00:53:02.919 --> 00:53:08.120
So I think being able to connect with different teams, understand sort of how it is that they

00:53:08.919 --> 00:53:12.360
where they are in their point of life or where they are in their development journey in order

00:53:12.360 --> 00:53:13.639
to be able to do these things.

00:53:14.600 --> 00:53:19.159
It's really important to be empathetic and learn and be able to take those learnings

00:53:19.159 --> 00:53:20.760
and bring it to other teams.

00:53:20.760 --> 00:53:26.199
And I think that's one thing that I find really cool about my job is like being able to connect

00:53:26.199 --> 00:53:31.800
with these different teams, bring learnings from different places, bring it to other teams,

00:53:31.800 --> 00:53:36.520
make those connections as well as like bring what are the problems that people are facing

00:53:36.520 --> 00:53:41.479
to like our different tools teams or to my other my tools team to be able to say like

00:53:41.479 --> 00:53:42.760
here are things that I'm hearing.

00:53:44.760 --> 00:53:45.639
What are your thoughts?

00:53:45.639 --> 00:53:52.280
And I think like a great example of this was another talk at Posit.com from GSK.

00:53:52.280 --> 00:53:57.479
We created this open source tool called Slushy, which is built on top of RM to do

00:53:58.040 --> 00:53:59.159
environment management.

00:53:59.800 --> 00:54:04.439
So I don't know if we would have ever gotten to that point without being able to go out

00:54:04.439 --> 00:54:09.239
to these different teams and like actually listen to what are their problems for how

00:54:09.239 --> 00:54:13.879
for what they're encountering if they want to use R for their for that creation of their

00:54:13.879 --> 00:54:14.280
outputs.

00:54:14.919 --> 00:54:19.399
Yeah, I was trying to go find a link to that talk, but I forgot they're not all public

00:54:19.399 --> 00:54:22.120
yet, but they will be in the next few months.

00:54:23.879 --> 00:54:28.520
Ben, was there anything that like after your talk you thought about?

00:54:28.520 --> 00:54:34.520
Oh, I wish I also covered this or maybe a question that was asked of you that you had

00:54:34.520 --> 00:54:35.479
wanted to expand on.

00:54:36.280 --> 00:54:40.120
Um, I think the biggest thing is.

00:54:42.120 --> 00:54:43.959
If you really want to.

00:54:46.040 --> 00:54:50.919
If you really want to enable learning, you actually need to put the support behind it.

00:54:50.919 --> 00:54:58.439
And I think the big thing that I wish I was more focused on in that talk was you can do

00:54:58.439 --> 00:55:00.360
as much training as you want.

00:55:01.159 --> 00:55:03.000
Um, but if you're not actually using it.

00:55:04.360 --> 00:55:09.399
In the creation of an output, that's that's where your you actually learn how to do things

00:55:09.399 --> 00:55:14.360
and there needs to be a really robust support team behind to help answer those questions.

00:55:14.360 --> 00:55:19.719
And I wish I kind of hit that more is just really focused on that support and mentoring.

00:55:19.719 --> 00:55:20.840
It's really hard to scale.

00:55:20.840 --> 00:55:25.560
I realize because it's, you know, actual hours and not, you know, a piece of document that

00:55:25.560 --> 00:55:29.959
someone can go read, but that that support and mentorship is crucial for for being able

00:55:29.959 --> 00:55:33.159
to change and enable an organization to use a tool.

